---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AuDHD vs ADHD: How the Autism Component Changes Things"
  description="AuDHD isn't just ADHD with extra traits. Learn how autism changes the ADHD experience and why standard ADHD strategies often fall short."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">AuDHD vs ADHD: Why Standard ADHD Advice Falls Short</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        If you have ADHD and the usual tips don't quite land, there might be a reason. AuDHD (autism + ADHD) looks like ADHD on the surface but operates differently underneath. Here's where they split apart.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Same Symptoms, Different Engine</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          ADHD and AuDHD can produce identical-looking symptoms. Trouble focusing, disorganization, difficulty with time, emotional reactivity. From the outside, they're indistinguishable. But the internal mechanics are different, and that matters for what actually helps.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          An ADHD person might struggle with focus because their brain isn't producing enough dopamine for a boring task. An AuDHD person might struggle with focus for that reason <em>plus</em> sensory overload from the open-plan office, social anxiety from the meeting they just left, and a rigid mental plan that got disrupted when a colleague asked an unexpected question. Same outcome. Very different causes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Why "Just Use a Planner" Doesn't Cut It</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          ADHD advice generally assumes your main problem is activation and follow-through. Get a planner, set reminders, use body doubling, break tasks into small steps. And for ADHD alone, these strategies genuinely help a lot of people.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          AuDHD throws wrenches into nearly all of them. Body doubling? Great, unless another person's presence is sensorily distracting (an autistic trait). Breaking tasks into small steps? Only works if you can tolerate the cognitive switching between steps (autistic rigidity makes this harder). Setting reminders? Helpful until the notification sound triggers sensory irritation and you disable all of them.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          The autism component adds constraints that standard ADHD hacks don't account for. So you try the thing everyone recommends, it doesn't work, and you conclude something is wrong with <em>you</em>. Nothing is wrong with you. The strategy was designed for a different brain.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Emotional Regulation: Two Layers Deep</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          ADHD emotional dysregulation is well-documented. Big feelings, fast reactions, rejection sensitivity. But people with ADHD alone can usually <em>identify</em> what they're feeling. They're angry. They're hurt. They know.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          AuDHD adds alexithymia to the mix. That's difficulty recognizing and naming your own emotions. So you're having an intense emotional reaction (ADHD amplification) and you can't figure out what the emotion actually <em>is</em> (autistic alexithymia). You just know something is very wrong. Is it anger? Sadness? Hunger? Overstimulation? All of them? Trying to calm down from an emotion you can't identify is like trying to fix a car when you don't know which part is broken.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Social Energy Works Differently</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          People with ADHD often recharge through social interaction. Talking to friends is stimulating, energizing. The social impulsivity (interrupting, dominating conversations) comes from enthusiasm, not malice, and the social battery usually stays charged during the interaction itself.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          For AuDHD, socializing is simultaneously stimulating and draining. You're energized by the conversation <em>while it's happening</em> because the ADHD brain loves the dopamine hit. But the autism processing cost catches up later. Two hours after the party, you're in bed with the lights off, completely wiped out and replaying every awkward moment. ADHD people might feel a post-social dip. AuDHD people often hit a wall.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Stimulation Needs Are Contradictory</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          ADHD brains are chronically understimulated. They seek novelty, movement, intensity. That's why ADHD people gravitate toward loud environments, multitasking, and risky behavior. More input equals more dopamine.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Autistic brains are often easily overstimulated. Too much input leads to overload, meltdowns, and shutdown. Now combine them. Your AuDHD brain is bored and overwhelmed at the same time. You need more stimulation to function, but you can only handle so much before your nervous system revolts. The window of "just right" is incredibly narrow, and it shifts throughout the day.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          Finding that sweet spot is one of the biggest practical challenges of AuDHD. Too little stimulation and you're paralyzed. Too much and you're melting down.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Medication Responses Can Be Unpredictable</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          ADHD medication (stimulants like methylphenidate or amphetamines) works well for many ADHD people. But AuDHD responses are less predictable. Some people find that stimulants help with focus but increase sensory sensitivity or anxiety (autistic traits that the medication doesn't address). Others find the right medication transformative but need different dosing than typical ADHD protocols suggest.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          This isn't a reason to avoid medication. It's a reason to work with a clinician who understands both conditions, not just one.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/autism-or-adhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Autism, ADHD, or Both? Take the quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/audhd-vs-autism/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD vs autism: key differences &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
